text.text: A Guide to Paddington

Famous railway station and fluffy marmalade addicts aside, there’s actually a colossal amount of cool stuff to do in this beautiful little nugget of West London. Perched on the edge of Hyde Park, this place is brimming with chic shops, markets, glam Georgian homes and an infamous collection of delicious Middle Eastern restaurants. Let’s have a ganders.
Best for... kebabs

tip.text: If you’re bored of the doner and up for one of the most spectacular kebab's of your life – hit up Hafez. Truth is, nowhere does kebabs quite like Persia and this joint is living proof of that fact. Most alluring has to be their Ghormeh Sabzi. Kidney beans, lamb, herbs and lime – this is Persia’s infamous stew and you’d be super silly to sleep on it.

Best for... scoffing steak

tip.text:
It’s common knowledge that cooking a steak takes great experience and knowledge. Thankfully for all inhabitants of London, the fine folk at Casa Malevo have got both going on.

Try the grilled lamb chops with anchovie salsa verde, with a side of potato and cabbage gratin and a glass of Argentinian wine - because that's the only type of wine they serve, but also because it's divine. Oh, and be sure to dollop excessive amounts of chimichurri on your plate. You won’t regret it.

Best for... getting your dim sum on

tip.text: It might be a little hard to find, but once you make it into this Cantonese-inspired restaurant and cocktail bar, you'll realise why it's so damn popular. The dim sum choice on offer here is a bit of a favourite as is the seafood, but we were digging the crispy Peking duck. It's excellent Chinese food; albeit at a cost that reflects it.

Best for... burgers, duh

tip.text:
Home to the juiciest burger going, you may have already heard of ‘The Juicy Bastard’ – seeing as it’s won a myriad of awards. It’s well worth the trip, even if you’re coming from Australia.

You’ll find it here in this charmingly grotty little boozer. Plus, this extremely good looking pub hosts wonderfully friendly staff and a fire beer selection to boot.

Best for... being a bookworm

tip.text:
When the founders of Monocle launch a retail space, you know it’s going to be rather spectacular. Kioskafé is situated just outside Paddington station and is a behemoth of independent magazines and phenomenal coffee – quite frankly – this is one of Paddington’s finest haunts to date.

Just how good is the coffee here? Well, it’s Allpress, so you know you’re in for a treat. This incredibly beautiful space is home to over a whopping 300 magazine titles and even has a print-on-demand catalogue (swoon), and even houses underwear, toothbrushes and umbrellas.

What more could you ever, ever want?

Best for... fusion food

tip.text:
Instead of the serious, precise sushi restaurants of Japan, Kurobuta models itself on the Japanese Izakaya - noisy Japanese drinking dens that serve pretty much any kind of food you can think of.

This place does Wagyu Beef Sliders on the one hand and Tempura Broad Beans with Wasabi Salt on the other. This is guilty, gourmet, Japanese junk food, just the way we like it.

Best for... spotting celebs

tip.text:
Built at the same time as Paddington Station (Around 1838), legend has it that Queen Victoria stopped off for a cold one on her way to catch a train, after which the pub was named in her honour. Appaz, Charles Dickens also spent time here writing Our Mutual Friend. Oh, and the joint was a favourite with Churchill and Charlie Chaplin. Oh Em Gee.

Despite all the name-dropping, this is a charming ol' watering hole. With its seriously stunning listed interior, cheap beers, and scrumptiously simple menu - this historic building should be your new pub-crawl staple. It’s a truly classic British boozer.

text.text: Built at the same time as Paddington Station (Around 1838), legend has it that Queen Victoria stopped off on her way to Paddington Station, and after that the pub was named in her honour. With its seriously stunning listed interior, cheap beers and scrumptiously simple menu - this historic building should be your new pub-crawl staple. It’s a truly classic British boozer.
Best for... artful dishes

tip.text:
Owners Luca Riccio and Franco de Todaro have done something insanely special with this little Connaught Village based Italian restaurant.

With each dish better resembling a pricey piece of art than something you're about to pop in your mouth - the mesmerizingly colourful plates flying out the kitchen here are really something to behold. It also helps that they're all downright delicious.

Best for... all things Thai

tip.text:
Underneath the rather unremarkable Heron pub is this diamond in the rough. Serving authentic Thai food, this spot offers more unusual (and delicious) traditional dishes, such as sour sausages and larb salad piled with fragrant minced meat.

The staff are really friendly which, combined with the mainly Thai clientèle and Thai Karaoke on the TV, makes this place as authentic as it gets.

text.text: You'll find this little Thai gem secretly tucked away under a friendly Paddington boozer. Basically, if you love Thai food you already know about this place. If you don't, give yourself a slap on the wrist and get down here ASAP.
Best for... sexy cocktails

tip.text:
Old Mary's is all about cocktails, craft beers and hot-dogs. Not exactly ground-breaking stuff here, but what they do, they do very well.

Hidden underneath a crappy Young's pub, Old Mary's is dark, candle-lit with a buzzing atmosphere. Great spot for a date or somewhere to get the night started with pals. After a few craft beers, the gourmet hot-dogs obviously go down a treat too.

text.text: This chic, basement bar is candle-lit, cute and oozing cool. Bountifully atmospheric, you’ll find an experimental cocktail menu on offer and a haunting tale. Folklore has it that Old Mary was a servant of the home’s owner Lord Craven – whom she stabbed in the heart. Chill.
